Now I can see the PF v6 `ExpandableSectionToggle` structure. Key observation: in v6, the toggle wrapper uses a dynamic class `${styles.expandableSection}__toggle` (which would resolve to something like `pf-v6-c-expandable-section__toggle`), but the **children** (text) are passed directly to a `Button` component — there's no `__toggle-text` wrapper element anymore.

The original CSS was:
```scss
.expandable-section-interface-type .pf-v5-c-expandable-section__toggle-text {
  font-weight: bold;
  color: var(--pf-global--Color--200);
}
```

This targeted the toggle text span inside the toggle. In v6, the children are rendered directly inside the `Button` component. The custom class `expandable-section-interface-type` is applied to the `ExpandableSectionToggle` component's outer `div` (via `className` prop). So to style the text, I should target the button's text content directly.

Looking at the v6 structure: the outer div gets `expandable-section-interface-type`, inside is a `__toggle` div, inside that is a `Button` (link variant). The text is directly inside the button. I can target this by using `.expandable-section-interface-type .pf-v6-c-button` or simply apply the styles directly on `.expandable-section-interface-type` since the text will inherit font-weight and color.

The simplest and most robust approach: apply the styles directly to `.expandable-section-interface-type` since `font-weight` and `color` are inherited CSS properties and will cascade to the button text.

